eed-forward sub-layers underscores its role in maintaining numerical stability throughout the deep encoder stack. [Data: Entities (33); Relationships (979)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Feed-Forward Networks provide position-wise non-linear transformations\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The FEED-FORWARD NETWORK (FFN) constitutes the second sub-layer in each ENCODER block and operates identically and independently on each position in the sequence. Composed of two linear transformations with a ReLU activation in between, the FFN typically expands the representation dimension (e.g., by 4x), applies non-linearity, and then projects back to the original dimension. This structure introduces essential non-linear capacity at every token position, complementing the contextual mixing performed by self-attention. The FFN’s position-wise nature ensures computational efficiency while enhancing model expressiveness. [Data: Entities (35, 50); Relationships (110, 99)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"The Embedding Layer supplies initial input representations to the Encoder\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The EMBEDDING LAYER serves as the entry point to the Transformer model, converting discrete input tokens into dense vector representations that are fed directly into the ENCODER. These embeddings encode semantic and syntactic information and are often augmented with positional encodings to retain sequence order information, which the encoder otherwise lacks due to its parallel processing nature. Without this initial transformation, the encoder would have no meaningful numerical input to process, making the embedding layer a prerequisite for the entire architecture. [Data: Entities (364); Relationships (632)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Encoder Pretraining enables self-supervised learning paradigms\",\n            \"explanation\": \"ENCODER PRETRAINING refers to the self-supervised training strategy used in 